segments.text: time phases because you see I have to consider four years before the war and then I have to consider one term and one summer after the war and before the war
I had a physics instructor named Veazey.
I think it was D.D.
Veazey.
I'm not sure.
That probably influenced me to continue and work in the engineering field.
After the war, I guess Spencer J. Buchanan had more effect on my schooling than anybody else.
He was in the Civil Engineering Department.
I guess he's a part-time instructor, if at all, now.
Buchanan, Burkhart & Associates has a geotechnical engineering firm in downtown Bryan.
Mr. Sandstett had a civil engineering department before the war.
was quite influential.
How did these men influence you?
By being willing and actually giving more of their time than just what took place between the bells.
And showing a sincere effort in your welfare,
What's going on?
How are you doing in other studies?
Things like that.
It's too easy to get into that.

The bell starts, the class starts, and when the bell rings, it's over, and turn your papers in, and when you come back, all the papers are spread across the desk, and find your own paper, and that's your grade.
I guess it's back to what I have always tried to teach to my subordinates as well as to my two sons.
Everybody is a human being.
They deserve to be treated like one.
And you can't treat everybody the same way.
Even if you're in a...

college or university, I don't care whether you've got 2,000 students or 32,000 students, the minute you start turning the crank and trying to treat everybody the same way, well, it's going to lose its personality, it's going to lose its character, and these men are not that type.
I
had a math instructor by the name of Halperin that, of course, I'll never forget.
But I don't know that he was a great influence on my life.
But he was by the name of Halperin.
You can figure that he's probably German.
But he was a calculus instructor.
He could start writing across the board, and he could write till the end of the period.
And he seemed to have eyes in the back of his head because we had these three benches.
They had a bench with three seats.
Each bench had three arms coming up.
And he seemed to know every time I get my feet up on the bench in front without ever turning around, Mr. Johnson, take your feet down.
I could never find the mirror.
I could never find a third eye.
I could never figure out where it was coming.
I remember one time after he told me twice, Mr. Johnson, take your feet down.
The third time he turned around and he hit me right in the head with a piece of chalk.
But I could never figure out how he knew that my feet were up there.
Did you think that A&M prepared you well to be an engineer?
Oh, yes.
I think that back in that day that was agricultural and engineering was definitely the long arm of A&M.
Hopefully some of the other schools at A&M.
I'm talking about some of the other departments have gotten stronger.
But agriculture and engineering were definitely the long arms.
I think since then there have been a number of other colleges and universities come up and approach them.
I would never say that it was on top unless

maybe the petroleum school at one time was and maybe it is now but i i don't just because i finished there i don't say that it was the number one engineering school in any particular discipline of engineering but you thought felt well prepared
Do you think that A&M changed your life?
Do you think that going there versus going to some other school made a difference in your career?
Oh, very good.
Very good.
Would you explain?
Well, I don't think that I would ever have
embarked on a military career by going to someplace like where my other buddies went, Rice or Sam Houston, either one.
Because rightfully or wrongfully, even though
One of them did come out as a colonel in the Marine Corps.
I believe that in the military that the individual is an officer first, and then whatever else he is, next.
be it engineer, supply man, or what, that if he's not the officer, then he's not going
to attain that top level.
I don't care whether it's top staff or commander or the top manager or what.
I guess the best way I can explain it is I've had too many engineers come to me and say, hey, I don't want to be a manager of engineers.
I want to be an engineer manager.
Okay.
You don't want to be the top man.
Then you realize you're drawing a line for yourself and you're not going to get above this line.
And it's probably Lieutenant Colonel.
You're never going to get above Lieutenant Colonel.
And you'll be lucky if you get that high.
Well,
I don't know.
I just want to practice engineering.
I said, okay.
If that's all you want to do is just practice engineering.
And I'm not belittling you because I happen to be an engineer myself and profess to be an engineer.
I've got a ticket hanging on the wall that says I am one because I'm a professional engineer, a registered engineer.
But we can buy them for a dime a dozen.
We can't buy the manager of engineers for down-to-date.
And I'm sure had I gone to Rice, I would have been a hell of a lot smarter civil engineer.
But I don't think I would have been any better off in any way than the manager.
Some people say that, most or a lot of people say that A&M is more than just an institution of higher learning, that there's something special, that it's sort of unique.
Would you agree with that?
Well, I used the term a while ago.
It's a living laboratory that the other places don't have.
Because I'm sure, you know, I've been to, well, let's take summer school.
Even summer school at A&M is a different life than core life, and probably a different life than long-term life during the regular school.
And you may or may not know those people who are living right next door.
And that's too often the case at other schools in the dormitories
Classes are mixed, freshman, sophomore, juniors.
You don't know who they are and what they are.
You go your way and I go mine.
Like too many communities in other parts of the world, other parts of the United States.
What about this idea of spirit?
Yeah, it's a hard thing to define.
It's there.
Sometimes I get a feeling that we attribute too much to it.
We get emotionally unstable.

some of the athletic contests where A&M has absolutely no chance of winning and yet the spirit will move a whole group of people and they'll feel that they've been mistreated if they didn't end up winning.
They lose
all sense of objectivity, but a spirit taking over, you know.
That's where it works against you.
It can also work for you, but...
I'm of the school that believes in spirit and tradition getting in there together, but tradition is only...
worthwhile so long as it serves for the body that established it and maintained it.
When it starts going against it, then that's the time to get rid of it.
So do you think there's a tradition of A&M or some of the spirit that should be taught, drawn along?
Sometimes I look at some and think that we're...
I wonder what they're serving, and yet I can rationalize with myself and say, well, you haven't been there so long.
For example?
Yeah, the...
We'll have to find the word.
The grooming, the adding, the things that the yell leaders go through to the public, all that make them look absolutely stupid.
to the way they walk, the way they carry their shoulders, some of the movements.
What in the hell is wrong with those guys?
And yet I can't say that's wrong.
And we did it 50 years ago.
But what does it do?
To me, I say now, what does it do?
Does it make a guy yell louder?
Does it set him off as, I am the leader, stay with me?
That's little.
That's trite.
Really what we're searching to concentrate on is large things that are
that are hurting us.
I don't know that there are, but I hate people to be in, I'm not going to use the word leadership, but yet the Yale leader is, by the title, he's in a position of leadership.
Yet sometimes he looks absolutely asinine.
He looks stupid.
Let's start on your military career.
Or is there something else you want to say about A&M before we move on to your military career when you were commissioned in 1941?
Well, it's currently whether we take it in two sections.
Well, we can come back.
I mean, if we say, yeah, my military career was like my college career.
It was split.
Yeah.
Sure, we can come back.
Were you happy when you received your commission, or would you have rather stayed at A&M and finished?
No, I was happy.
You were ready to leave?
Well, caught up with the group, I was like everybody else.
If the group's going, I want to go.
Even though you asked for a deferment?
Yeah, the college automatically asked for a deferment for all of us.
Oh, I see.
You did not personally.
I wanted it.
I didn't tell the college, don't ask for it.
Before we get into the service, are you a former student?
How long have you been there and how much do you know about life in the Corps?
Well, I know a lot because I've talked to a lot of generals.
Back when I was in school, the Corps wasn't much larger than it is now, maybe about twice the size.
And daily, we'd have a cadet officer of the day and a cadet officer of the guard.
And they were always under arms, under saber.
And during the spring, each regiment would have its own ball on a Friday night.
the following night there would be a core dance, which would be open to the entire school.
And as each regiment had its festivities, it would have a parade on the drill ground, just a regimental parade.
And it was up to the OD and the OG to be sure that
The conduct was maintained and the dress was maintained.
People just didn't come around the parade dressed like everybody because it had an awful lot of visitors at each regimental parade.
And the composite regiment was made up of the chem warfare and the signal corps.
And at the weekend that they had their parade involved,
I was introduced to a young lady that you met at the door down.
And she was there as a date with someone else.
And then, of course, a member of the Combined Regiment.
He's Kim Walker, actually.
And that night, well, the OD and the OG, no matter what regiment they belong to, they go and
One of them is always under saber and the other one could go out and dance or socialize and then come back and relieve the other one.
But one of them was always under saber.
He was the cadet in charge at that function.
So I danced with her that night whenever I could.
And then the next day, the same people that introduced me to her said,
wouldn't you eat lunch with her since her date is a table waiter?
And I said, yes, I'd enjoy it.
Then I was off duty.
Somebody else was the OD and the OD.
Well, I had such an enjoyable time eating lunch with her that I came right back to the battery, and I called all the freshmen and the sophomore for the battery together.
And I said, who all is going to the dance tonight?
Dismissed.
Dismissed.
Who wants to go to the dance tonight?
And I picked one freshman and one sophomore.
First, I said, who's got tucks?
One, you, and you.
OK.
So the game is late.
The freshmen cannot cut in on seniors.
Sophomore can.
Saturday night, she danced with one freshman, one sophomore, and me, and not with her own team.
Well, it didn't take but about three months, and then we went through the ring, and we were engaged by the time when the commission came along, and married very shortly thereafter.
So that was 1941, then?
Yep, that's 1941.
And where's your wife from?
Is she from Bryan, then?
She's from Missouri City, Texas, which is a little town.
By Houston.
Yep, just west of Houston.
Now, it wasn't as large as it is now.
They measured populations like 36, 37.
And she came up to A&M for the dance?
For the regimental ball.
So then you got married and went?
October.
October of 41.
Went on active duty in July and married in October.
OK, let's start talking about your active duty.
You send me just one sheet here on your military career.
OK, my senior year.
The Army Air Corps came into all the engineering schools enticing engineering students to put in transfer to the Army Air Corps.
They could see a buildup and they could see a need of engineers.
And I put in for a transfer to the Army Air Corps.
But when commissioning came along, those things had not come through, so I was commissioned in the field artillery.
I had orders to go to Fort Bliss and then go to Fort Sill to go to the artillery school.
That's where all the others went, like Becker and all that stuff.
Okay, but I was still wondering about this other piece of paper.
So I came over here to Fort Sam, started running it down, and they said, well, it's still pending, and as far as we know, you're still going to go to Bliss, and then you'll go on up to Sill.
And we're going to issue you a set of orders.
So they did.
And I got my foot marker back and everything, and I was getting ready to head out to El Paso, living in Houston at that time.

all of a sudden the wire came in and transferred to the air corps reserve non-rated and headed to brookly field mobile alabama so they're just the same number of miles but in the opposite direction so i got over there and i was about the 16th officer to report to this brand new base and it was still being constructed i mean we were in mud up to here and really yeah and uh
As often as I have found the ingenuities of the service, they didn't need engineers over there at that time.
But they needed administrative officers.
So they sent me off to the Adjutant General School up in Washington, DC.
As soon as you got there?
Well, very shortly.
I was up there at the time.
No, December 41.
Yeah, December 41.
I was in Washington on 7 December.
Tell me about that.
We had gotten married.
And do you, by chance, know a man around College Station, Lucian Morgan?
OK.
He's in the insurance business.
And he lived out south side of College Station.
But he was one of the students.
He was the first lieutenant at the school.
And I was the second lieutenant.
My wife had come up.
Lucian and another lieutenant named Johnson and myself were up actually visiting the Gettysburg battlefield on that Sunday.
We stopped at a little cafe to get something to eat.
We walked in and there wasn't anyone in the cafe.
Nobody behind a counter, nobody behind a cash register, nobody sitting at the table.
We sat down and then all of a sudden we heard coming from the kitchen this radio broadcast.
Well, the three of the men, we cleared the counter and went into the kitchen, and that's where we heard of the bombing.
On the way back... What were your thoughts?
Oh, what does someone think?
I don't know what our thoughts really were.
We knew it was coming sooner or later, but had no idea it was coming on that side.
Everybody was looking toward Europe.
You thought the Germans would attack before the Japanese?
Yeah, sure.
So on the way back from Gettysburg to the cantonment where the school is, we had to come right by the Japanese embassy.
And as we came by, you could see the flames on the inner court burning up over the top of the building.
They were just burning everything they could get their hands on that night.
All their documents?
Yeah, all their stuff.
Were there any Americans outside protesting?
No, the police had things pretty well under control, keeping people away.
Was Washington congested, or was there a lot of people, or was it confusion?
Yeah, a little confusion, and of course, the military department still worked in uniforms.
It was one of these one-day-a-week deal of wearing uniforms.
To see some of the Navy boys turn out in December in whites looked pretty cold.
Yeah.
That's all they had was white.
They managed to get by for years without having a wardrobe uniform.
So they were civilian clothes.
Well, our school was cut short by a couple of weeks.
All of us that had leave, the leaves were canceled.
And we all had to go right back to duty stations instead of go home for Christmas and so on.
And that was probably the greatest hardship.
By the time we got back to Mobile,
There were enough people that had come in in the six weeks and had filled up all of the apartments in town.
And it pushed us out to an area called Hollinger Island, south of Mobile.
And all that was out there were summer cottages, single frame, single floor.
No sheetrock walls, no walls at all, except just the outside wall.
It was pretty cool.
But we managed to make it.
We made some friendships there.
And what did the Air Force have you do?
What was your duty there?
When I reported in, I became the assistant base adjutant.
Because, again, they didn't need engineers.
And then they sent me off to the Adjutant General School, which even strengthened that you're going to be an administrative officer.
So when I came back, I went back to the job.
as assistant base adjutant for just a couple of weeks because then we started activating what was known as air depot groups.
Air depot group is an organization that does second and third echelon supply and maintenance in the Air Corps.
It goes and sets up and operates as a depot just as, you might say, like Kelly does here or like Tinker does up in Oklahoma.
Aircraft are brought into it for modifications and repair and so on.
It can't be done down at the unit level.
There were already some in existence in Georgia.
So a team of us went over and spent some time with them to see how they operated and how they were farmed and so on.
Then came back to Mobile, uh, Brooklyn and started farming these air depot groups.
And the first one that was farmed was the seventh air depot group.
And, uh, I became the commanding officer of the headquarters squadron and, uh, we had
supply squadron and repair squadron and we had quartermaster truck company and a chemical warfare platoon and a bunch of attached units.
We were fortunate because being the first one formed, because as these people came in from the different training schools and came in and went into the personnel pool, we had first grab at them.
and actually took the best qualified that we could to our own outfit, and then the 24th and the 25th was farm and so on, and so we had what we thought was a pretty good outfit.
About how many men?
A group had right at 1,200 men.
I had about 160 men in the headquarters squadron, and plus the...
quartermaster and the Kim Warfares were attached to me.
I had three at that time.
I was first and I had three second lieutenant subordinate.
All three of them were ROTC graduate.
One of them was a pilot and his job when we set up
he would be the base operations officer.
He would control the flight line.
And within our squadron were the people that worked for him.
And the headquarters commander was also the director of personnel for the entire group.
So I knew the personnel man.
We had some cute things happen.
We had probably the best engineer officer that ever walked in the
Air Corps and the Air Force named Kroeber.
And he was the commanding officer of the repair squadron.
He was a captain when we got ready to leave and they came down and just picked him out because he was German born, German trained, military, everything.
And he was a classmate of some of the higher people in Germany.
No way.
You're not going to Europe.
You may go to the Pacific, but you're not going to Europe.
Or leave him in command and put somebody else in there.
What did you think about that?
Well, we all hated to see it because by then we had established a pretty good outfit.
He was a captain, Captain Honeycutt, commander of the supply squadron.
They go by Huntsville now.
All three of us had what we thought were crackerjack squadrons, and we had a good outfit.
Anything that happened to it, well, you know, I just don't really know what to think about.
But then the longer you were away from it and you could see it, then you realized it was probably the best for security, and even though the guy
I knew him later in life as a full colonel, and he was clear of everything.
It was just one of those things.
A very interesting thing happened that later came back to, I'm sure, assist.
I had a pay officer by the name of Loren Durkee.
He was one of my second lieutenants.
At that time, enlisted personnel were paid
in cash at the pay table.

Come up, salute the pay officer, and the sergeant would sit there and read off how much he got, and the pay officer would hand him so much money, and the guy would sign on the line and turn around and walk off.
We got through paying the squadron, and we had $94 left on the table.
He came to me and said, what do we do?
And I said, First Sergeant, I said, Sergeant Hartman, call the squadron back in.
So we hadn't given anybody permission to leave the post.
I said, call the squadron back in.
And went down the amount that everybody was to be paid, had everybody checked to be sure that they'd gotten that much money.
Went back over to the finance officer where we'd drawn the money.
You're clear.
You're all right.
So they said, what are we going to do with it?
I said, okay, you're sitting on an order to turn in all of our athletic equipment tomorrow back to the base.
We can't take it with us.
We already knew we were leaving.
We can't take it with us.
You and Sergeant Hartman go downtown to Mobile tomorrow and buy $94 worth of athletic equipment.
List it.
Spread it in the squadron so we know where it is.
And when we got to England, we were the only outfit that had any athletic equipment.
We had $94 worth of athletic equipment.
Paid off before we ever got there.
The third day out, we had a boat drill out in the Atlantic.
And I'd been down visiting my troops.
We were in little cabins, but they were down below.
While I was down there, they rang the siren before we hit our side spot on the deck.
And I had no sooner got on the deck than somebody yelled, Lieutenant Johnson doesn't have a life preserver.
In 15 seconds, one hit me right behind the head.
I don't have any idea where it came from, but it came from somewhere in that squadron.
Huh?
No, it was a life preserver.
But boy, had I been caught on that deck without that life preserver, they would have ripped me from one end to the other.
But somebody in that squadron took care of it.
That's right.
Before we ever left Mobile.
When did you leave?
How long were you there?
We left in...
July of 42.
So I got back from the Adjutant General School in December just before Christmas.
In seven months we had formed the outfit and had gone up to Dick's and we pulled out in July.
While we were there, for instance, this is back to the old Harvey way of doing things,
Sometimes it works and sometimes it doesn't.
I very casually, at a standby inspection, one day said to one of the enlisted men, I said, I believe you've got your socks and your handkerchiefs crossed that belong in the opposite corner.
I got to the door while I hear this, and I said, son of a bitch, who the hell is making this?
Well, the next day, the boy was pretty well beat up, apparently.
And I asked the first sergeant, I said, do you have any idea what happened to this man?
He said, no, but the duty corporal and he were down on the beach last night.
And this was, we were still close enough to regular Army troops that that was still prevalent in, well, I had a,
first sergeant that went off to officer's training school.
And I called the next sergeant up and said, okay, Sergeant Prattman, you've inherited this first sergeant's job.
And he says, Lieutenant, says, not me.
He says, this thing is going to be a civilian man's army, and it's rapidly becoming one.
You don't want another one of us to be your first sergeant.
He was a career officer?
Huh?
Was he a civilian or a career officer?
No, he was a career non-commissioned officer.
Right, okay.
That's right.
He said, you don't want me.
He said, if you can find me one more strike somewhere, I'd appreciate it.
He said, but the man you want to be first sergeant of this squadron is Sergeant Hartman.
Hartman...
had been a selectee, he had come in the draft route.
So we gave them each one more strike, and then later on gave Ortman one more strike.
And when we sailed, Ortman was the first sergeant.
Fought like a selectee, worked like a guy that had been drafted.
Perfect set up.
Some of these old boys were sharp.
Some of them knew that.
Things were changing fast enough that they'd be completely out of place.
Because, man, that old system, it could get rough.
Mobile was an interesting place.
It later became one of the largest depots and kept turning these,
air depot groups out.
Unfortunately, when we got to England, I keep saying all of our efforts were wasted because we got there mighty, mighty early and they didn't yet need air depot groups, but later
As I got in other jobs, I realized that you can't move all the checkers at one time.
You've got to keep putting them in there, you know, and sooner or later you've got everything you need.
But we could have gone over a year or 18 months later and still been there on time.
So what did you do when you arrived in July of 1942?
In August, yeah.
In August, whereabouts, where were you stationed?
That's interesting.
We debarked.
at Swansea, Wales.
And Swansea is a tidal port.
You come in with the tide.
And if you're little, you stay afloat.
And if you're big, you sit on the bottom and wait till the tide comes in to take you back out.
Well, we got in just in time.
And we sat on the bottom and then leaned over against the dock.
And so there the ship was leaning against the dock.
Everybody got on the trains.
And they went all over the United Kingdom.
Well, our destination was Warrington.
Warrington sits between Liverpool and Manchester.
So it's in that part of the country.
And the night that we got to Warrington, we weren't quite yet where we were supposed to be.
Jerry made one of his last big raids just starting at Manchester and just dropping all the way to Liverpool.
So that was a big industrial area.
Not precision bombing, just hat-hazard bombing.
Well, the train stopped.
I turned to Sergeant Hartman and I said, Sergeant, get these men off this train.
And he and the other sergeant, I bet they cleared that train in about 30 seconds.
They went out the windows, they went out the doors, they went between cars, they went out the top ventilators.
They got off that train every way imaginable.
We didn't lose a single guy.
Was the train hit?
Yeah.
But that was our baptism.
Well, we got to a place called Burtonwood, and we sat there, and we sat there, and we used our $94 worth of sport equipment.
Really wasn't anything to do for about a month, I guess.
And then they started tapping the entire group to...
manned different outfits all over the United Kingdom.
Before it was over with, the 7th Air Department had practically lost its identity of personnel.
It hadn't lost its name.
I went from there up to Prestwick, Scotland, and became the Air Corps base adjutant up there sitting on an RAF base.
It's both a municipal field and an RAF base.
Had some pretty interesting incidents.
We had, well, this pilot was subordinate to me, went up also with me, and his name was Jarvis.
He's a Mormon from Salt Lake.
And we had to put a detachment way up in the Herbides that went up.
Air Corps was flying across the North Atlantic.
If they couldn't make it all the way down into Scotland, they'd make an emergency landing in the Hermitage.
So we put one officer and six enlisted men up there that could work on the aircraft and hopefully get it flying so the guy could continue on into Prestwick if they made the emergency landing.
And he'd fly me up there and pay the troops, and we'd take care of it.
We were about two miles from Johnny Walker's plant at Kilmarnock and since the RAF had an arrangement with the plant they included us and so they gave us
at the plant to defend if Jerry were to make a parachute landing on the plant.
Oh, yeah.
Well, it was a lot of fun and socializing, too, because we'd go over and make dry runs, you know, which would end up being very wet runs.
But everybody would go into position and make out like Jerry was coming over, and then they'd close down the station and then pull out the scotch bags, and everybody started drinking scotch.
But it was interesting.
How did you get along with the British and the RAF?
Well, pretty good, especially the Scots people up there were fine people.
We hadn't flooded the island to the extent that we were in their heritage.
This was still, this was 42.
So it was great.
They're happy to see you.
Yeah.
At least somebody's going to be in this thing with us, you know.
Whether they go down with us or not, we don't know.
But, you know, a good feeling.
That was back in the day when the northern bomb site was quite a secret thing.
I mean, boy, they controlled it, you know, under guard all the time.
That was the biggest thing that we had for the bombers.
Well, Prestwick was the northern port that the aircraft would enter coming into the United Kingdom.

And after making a run across the North Atlantic, which might take a guy two or three days, you know, stopping here and there and so on, they'd park out there on this great big old grass ramp and open the door and then just start throwing out the tomato cans and the trash.
And then some of our crews would have to go out and clean up the ramp as they moved on down into the kingdom.
And sure enough, somebody found a Norton bomb site.
They found it on Sunday, the one day that my office wasn't open.
He brought it over to the passenger traffic terminal and says, turn this in to Lieutenant Johnson tomorrow.
Norton bomb site.
Just put Lieutenant Johnson's name on it and stick it down under the counter.
Believe it or not, three weeks later, intelligence came up from London.
